<input type="hidden" name="course" value="problemset">
<input type="hidden" name="task" value="2229">
Your task is to count the number of permutations of $1,2,\dots,n$ that have exactly $k$ inversions (i.e., pairs of elements in the wrong order).<br />
<br />
For example, when $n=4$ and $k=3$, there are $6$ such permutations:<ul>
<li> $[1,4,3,2]$<br />
<li> $[2,3,4,1]$<br />
<li> $[2,4,1,3]$<br />
<li> $[3,1,4,2]$<br />
<li> $[3,2,1,4]$<br />
<li> $[4,1,2,3]$<br />
</ul>
<b id="input">Input</b><br />
<br />
The only input line has two integers $n$ and $k$.<br />
<br />
<b id="output">Output</b><br />
<br />
Print the answer modulo $10^9+7$.<br />
<br />
<b id="constraints">Constraints</b><br />
<ul>
<li>$1 \le n \le 500$<br />
<li>$0 \le k \le \frac{n(n-1)}{2}$<br />
</ul>
<b id="example">Example</b><br />
<br />
Input:<br />
<code>4 3</code><br />
<br />
Output:<br />
<code>6</code>    </div>
